{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:32:58.168352+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "The comment failed due to a permissions issue (the provided PAT lacks write access to this repository). Let me note this limitation and provide my triage assessment here instead.\n\n---\n\n**Triage Summary for Issue #1: `apply_migrations.sh applies files in wrong order on filesystems with case-folding`**\n\n**My assessment: This is likely a false diagnosis — the issue should remain open but reclassified.**\n\n**Why the reported root cause is wrong:**\n- The script uses `for f in migrations/*.sql` (shell glob expansion), which sorts lexicographically.\n- The filenames `001_create_users.sql`, `002_create_sessions.sql`, `003_add_session_index.sql` differ only in leading **digits**. Digits are not affected by case-folding (APFS) or `LC_COLLATE` variations — only letters are. So `001 < 002 < 003` is universal.\n- The issue claims case-insensitive APFS + non-C locale causes wrong sort order. This is factually incorrect for digit-only differences.\n\n**Why the intermittent failure contradicts the diagnosis:**\n- A glob-sorting problem would be **deterministic** (same wrong order every run on a given system).\n- The commenter reports \"~3 out of 5 runs\" fail, which is **inconsistent** with a deterministic ordering bug.\n- An intermittent failure points to a different root cause, most likely **PostgreSQL not being fully ready** in the Docker container when migrations run.\n\n**Recommended actions (that I was unable to perform due to the 403 permission error):**\n1. **Comment** on the issue explaining the above analysis.\n2. **Keep the issue open** but reclassify — the real fix likely involves adding a readiness check (e.g., `pg_isready`) before running migrations and adding `--fail-on-error` to the `psql` invocation so the script halts on the first failure.\n\n**Limitation:** I was unable to post the comment to GitHub due to a 403 (PAT lacks write access to this 